that President Obama said in his
news conference

18:31.577 --> 18:33.346 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
on Friday.

18:33.379 --> 18:37.083 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He said: "By so many measures,
our country
is stronger and more prosperous
than it was

18:37.116 --> 18:38.451 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
when we started."

18:38.484 --> 18:41.687 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He said: "It's a situation I'm
proud to leave
for my successor.

18:41.721 --> 18:45.725 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's thanks to the American
people, to the
work you have put in, the
sacrifices you have

18:45.758 --> 18:47.560 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
made."

18:47.593 --> 18:52.398 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Does Mr. Trump believe what Mr.
Obama said,
that the country is stronger and
more prosperous

18:52.431 --> 18:55.534 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
as a result or at the end of the
Obama presidency?

18:55.568 --> 18:58.104 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
KELLYANNE CONWAY: Well, by some
measures,
we are.

18:58.137 --> 19:00.373 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But if you look at the polls,
Americans don't
feel that way.

19:00.406 --> 19:03.876 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
If they felt that way, they
would have given
Hillary Clinton and Barack Obama
a third term.

19:03.909 --> 19:10.182 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He himself campaigned mightily
across the
country for her, basically
making that case.

19:10.216 --> 19:14.186 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He said to people, I will take
it personally,
this is my legacy on the line.

19:14.220 --> 19:15.955 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And people rejected that call.

19:15.988 --> 19:18.591 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think people feel like there
is a little
bit of unfinished business,
Judy.

19:18.624 --> 19:21.961 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There is no question that you
have millions
of Americans still lacking
health insurance.

19:21.994 --> 19:25.965 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You have millions of Americans,
particularly
women and children, in poverty
as you and

19:25.998 --> 19:27.900 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
I speak tonight.

19:27.933 --> 19:32.371 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You have a lot of unfinished
business, but
obviously every president who
leaves, particularly

19:32.405 --> 19:36.142 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
after two terms, can point to
many different
areas where there has been
progress and there

19:36.175 --> 19:37.943 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
has been change.

19:37.977 --> 19:40.646 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I would expect President
Obama to do what
President George W. Bush did
when he left,

19:40.679 --> 19:44.617 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and President Bill Clinton when
he left, which
is to point to those numbers of
improvement.

19:44.650 --> 19:47.820 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Let me finally
ask you about
what President Obama did today.

19:47.853 --> 19:52.892 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He announced a ban on new oil
and gas drilling
on the Atlantic Coast from New
England to

19:52.925 --> 19:54.193 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
the Chesapeake Bay.

19:54.226 --> 19:56.495 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Canada announced something in
conjunction
with this.

19:56.529 --> 20:00.066 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Is this something that Mr. Trump
is going
to let stand?

20:00.099 --> 20:03.702 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
KELLYANNE CONWAY: Well, I would
need to discuss
that with him, and he will make
those decisions

20:03.736 --> 20:05.004 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
as the president.

20:05.037 --> 20:07.273 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But I will remind us all what
his policy towards
energy is.

20:07.306 --> 20:09.542 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's basically -- and everybody
can read it
for themselves.

20:09.575 --> 20:14.313 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
As part of his 100-day plan,
Judy, president-elect
Trump has made very clear that
unleashing

20:14.346 --> 20:19.318 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
our energy sources here at home
is an incredibly
important aspect of that.

20:19.351 --> 20:20.820 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Why?

20:20.853 --> 20:25.658 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Because we need to invest in all
energy sources,
including coal and shale.

20:25.691 --> 20:28.360 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We have energy literally off our
shores and
under our feet.

20:28.394 --> 20:31.330 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Well, it sounds
like he's going
to reverse it, from what you're
saying.

20:31.363 --> 20:33.199 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(CROSSTALK)

20:33.232 --> 20:34.233 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
KELLYANNE CONWAY: Well, it makes
us more -- well,
you're asking me about a
specific policy move,

20:34.266 --> 20:35.468 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
and I can't comment on that.

20:35.501 --> 20:37.303 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It would be unfair to the
president-elect.

20:37.336 --> 20:41.140 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But I will tell you, if you look
at his plan,
he's going to go farther than
other presidents

20:41.173 --> 20:47.346 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
have gone in terms of making us
more dependent
on ourselves energy-wise, and to
create billions

20:47.379 --> 20:51.884 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of dollars in revenue, millions
of jobs, some
people project, over time.

20:51.917 --> 20:56.889 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And it also means that we're
less dependent
on some of these foreign powers
for our energy

20:56.922 --> 20:59.658 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
sources, which I know many
Americans would
appreciate.

20:59.692 --> 21:04.163 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
What's a major concern that
people, major
grievance Americans lodge, Judy?

21:04.196 --> 21:05.798 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It's, we don't make anything in
America anymore.

21:05.831 --> 21:06.799 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Well, you know what?

21:06.832 --> 21:08.834 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Energy is in America.

21:08.868 --> 21:14.306 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And if we can tap into that
safely and appropriately,
I guarantee that is something
that President

21:14.340 --> 21:18.611 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Trump will certainly look into
in a very serious
way.

21:18.644 --> 21:22.214 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Kellyanne Conway,
adviser to
the president-elect, we thank
you.

21:22.248 --> 21:23.749 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
KELLYANNE CONWAY: Thank you,
Judy.

21:23.782 --> 21:28.120 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
All the best.

21:28.154 --> 21:38.898 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: And in other
White House
news, according to a New York
Times report,

21:38.931 --> 21:44.904 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the Obama administration has
notified Congress
it plans to transfer 17 or 18
prisoners from

21:44.937 --> 21:50.242 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
the detention center at
Guantanamo Bay, Cuba,
before president-elect Trump
takes office.

21:50.276 --> 21:54.713 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
In all, the military prison has
housed nearly
780 detainees.

21:54.747 --> 21:58.517 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
That number was down to 242 by
time President
Obama took office.

21:58.551 --> 22:04.823 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Today, there are 59 remaining,
including 22
who have been approved for
transfer to other

22:04.857 --> 22:05.991 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
countries.

22:06.025 --> 22:09.228 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
That's if certain security
conditions were
met there.

22:09.261 --> 22:14.567 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
After this latest batch of
transfers, 41 or
42 prisoners would be left at
Guantanamo Bay

22:14.600 --> 22:17.903 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
for Mr. Trump's administration
to handle.

22:17.937 --> 22:20.105 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Joining me now for more on this
process is
Charlie Savage.

22:20.139 --> 22:24.577 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He's a Washington correspondent
at The New
York Times and author of "Power
Wars: Inside

22:24.610 --> 22:25.911 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Obama's Post-9/11 Presidency."

22:25.945 --> 22:28.047 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Thanks for joining us.

22:28.080 --> 22:31.283 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, who are these batch of
prisoners that
are being transferred?

22:31.317 --> 22:32.818 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Why them and why not the rest of
them?

22:32.851 --> 22:34.520 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
CHARLIE SAVAGE, The New York
Times: Right.

22:34.553 --> 22:39.525 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, of the men at Guantanamo,
not all of them
are cleared for transfer.

22:39.558 --> 22:43.996 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There's 10 that are facing
charges before
a military commission, and
there's about just

22:44.029 --> 22:49.735 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
under 30 who the government has
not charged
with a crime, but officials
believe they are

22:49.768 --> 22:51.403 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
still too dangerous to release.

22:51.437 --> 22:55.374 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And so they continue to be held
as wartime
detainees, essentially.

22:55.407 --> 22:58.077 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And then there are these lists
you mentioned
of about 22 men.

22:58.110 --> 23:03.515 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
That's the remnants of what used
to be a very
long list of people who six
agencies looked

23:03.549 --> 23:08.254 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
at and decided could be safely
released, as
long as they went to a country
that could

23:08.287 --> 23:12.925 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
provide certain security
assurances, like
monitoring them and preventing
them from travel

23:12.958 --> 23:14.760 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
and so forth.

23:14.793 --> 23:19.598 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In his last sort of second part
of his second
term, Obama has made a big push
to get that

23:19.632 --> 23:24.436 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
list down as close to zero as he
can before
he leaves office, even if he
fails to close

23:24.470 --> 23:26.205 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
the prison.

23:26.238 --> 23:28.173 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Now, closing
the prison
was something the president
wanted, but it

23:28.207 --> 23:29.775 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
also had bipartisan support.

23:29.808 --> 23:30.776 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Why didn't it happen?

23:30.809 --> 23:33.345 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
CHARLIE SAVAGE: So, you're
right.

23:33.379 --> 23:37.583 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The Bush administration in its
second term
wanted to close Guantanamo.

23:37.616 --> 23:43.122 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And in the 2008 presidential
election, both
Obama and his Republican
opponent, John McCain,

23:43.155 --> 23:45.357 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
said that they would close
Guantanamo.

23:45.391 --> 23:50.429 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, when Obama came in and said
he would close
the prison within a year, it
looked like it

23:50.462 --> 23:55.934 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
wasn't a partisan or a
controversial policy
to be working towards.

23:55.968 --> 24:02.441 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But the politics shifted under
his feet over
the course of 2009-2010.

24:02.474 --> 24:08.213 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so, at that point, Congress
started imposing
restrictions on the transfers of
detainees,

24:08.247 --> 24:12.685 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
including eventually banning
them and their
transfer to the United States
for any purpose.

24:12.718 --> 24:17.990 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And President Obama's plan,
often overlooked,
for closing Guantanamo wasn't to
release every

24:18.023 --> 24:21.560 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
detainee who could not be
charged with a crime.

24:21.593 --> 24:26.965 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There was that group of two or
three dozen
who the administration itself
thought was

24:26.999 --> 24:28.801 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
too dangerous to release, but
could not be
charged.

24:28.834 --> 24:33.439 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And his plans, then, to close
the prison as
to move them to a different
prison in the

24:33.472 --> 24:39.745 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
United States, where they would
be cheaper
to house and where the symbolic
sort of notoriety

24:39.778 --> 24:44.616 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of Guantanamo, the location the
Bush administration
had used, would go away.

24:44.650 --> 24:48.454 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, once Congress banned him
from bringing
prisoners into the United
States, that plan

24:48.487 --> 24:49.688 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
could not work.

24:49.722 --> 24:52.291 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And, therefore, basically, he
wasn't going
to close it.

24:52.324 --> 24:55.961 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And the only question was, would
the U.S.
get rid of the people at least
that it didn't

24:55.994 --> 25:00.065 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
actually want to hold, this long
list of detainees
approved for transfer?

25:00.099 --> 25:02.167 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: What about
concerns about
recidivism?

25:02.201 --> 25:07.306 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CHARLIE SAVAGE: The reengagement
rate of detainees
who were released in the Bush
administration

25:07.339 --> 25:11.577 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
is about 30 percent, suspected
or confirmed,
a little over 30 percent.

25:11.610 --> 25:15.547 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And that's because, during the
Bush years,
large numbers of detainees were
sent home

25:15.581 --> 25:21.186 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to places like Afghanistan and
Saudi Arabia
in bulk transfers after
President Bush decided

25:21.220 --> 25:23.722 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
to start trying to close the
prison.

25:23.756 --> 25:27.793 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The Obama administration has
pursued a different
approach, an individualized
approach.

25:27.826 --> 25:33.432 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It has a process where six
national security
agencies look at individual
detainees and

25:33.465 --> 25:35.768 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
have to agree that that person
is releasable.

25:35.801 --> 25:39.972 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And there's a lot more planning
for where
they're going to go and what
kind of sort

25:40.005 --> 25:45.277 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
of reentry into society,
monitoring, travel
restrictions and so forth
they're going to

25:45.310 --> 25:47.513 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
encounter once they get out.

25:47.546 --> 25:52.551 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And that has brought down the
recidivism rate
for Obama era transfers to about
12 percent,

25:52.584 --> 25:54.319 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
confirmed or suspected.

25:54.353 --> 25:57.289 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: What do we
know about the
Trump administration's plans for
Guantanamo

25:57.322 --> 25:59.091 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Bay?

25:59.124 --> 26:00.859 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CHARLIE SAVAGE: President Trump
has said he
will keep Guantanamo open and
that he will

26:00.893 --> 26:02.327 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
bring new detainees there.

26:02.361 --> 26:05.330 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He famously said he would load
it up with
some bad dudes.

26:05.364 --> 26:09.701 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Obama, of course, was trying to
close it and
failed, but didn't bring anyone
new there

26:09.735 --> 26:14.440 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in his entire eight years as
president, and
chipped away at the detainee
population.

26:14.473 --> 26:19.378 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, I think we can safely
predict that, sooner
or later, in the Trump
administration, the

26:19.411 --> 26:23.715 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
United States government will
capture a terrorism
suspect and bring him to
Guantanamo.

26:23.749 --> 26:28.587 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And he will be the first new
prisoner there
in quite a long time.

26:28.620 --> 26:33.792 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
What we don't know is whether
president-elect
Trump intends to shut down all
transfers of

26:33.826 --> 26:39.798 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
lower-level detainees to get rid
of the six-agency
review kind of parole board-like
process,

26:39.832 --> 26:45.170 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
or whether he will continue that
process,
just without -- not using it
very often.

26:45.204 --> 26:47.973 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: How much does
it cost to
keep Guantanamo running?

26:48.006 --> 26:55.380 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
CHARLIE SAVAGE: The operating
cost of Guantanamo
in 2015 was $450 million.

26:55.414 --> 27:01.119 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And so if the Obama
administration does succeed
in getting roughly 18, plus or
minus, detainees

27:01.153 --> 27:09.127 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
out, that would break down to a
ratio of about
$10 million per detainee per
year to house

27:09.161 --> 27:10.929 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
them at Guantanamo.

27:10.963 --> 27:15.334 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There are some asterisks to
that, because
that figure includes the cost of
the military

27:15.367 --> 27:18.704 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
commission system as well, which
is not cheap
at all.

27:18.737 --> 27:20.439 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Charlie Savage
of The New
York Times, thanks so much.

27:20.472 --> 27:24.643 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
CHARLIE SAVAGE: Thank you.

27:24.676 --> 27:36.922 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Now we have a
story about possible
changes as a result of the
election.

27:36.955 --> 27:42.427 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Some American women say they
fear they could
lose their access to birth
control once president-elect

27:42.461 --> 27:44.229 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Trump takes office.

27:44.263 --> 27:49.635 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Trump has pledged to repeal the
Affordable
Care Act, which includes free
contraceptives.

27:49.668 --> 27:54.239 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He hasn't said what would
replace it, and
that's why the women in this
story are taking

27:54.273 --> 27:55.440 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
action.

27:55.474 --> 27:58.343 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Correspondent Lisa Desjardins
has the story.

27:58.377 --> 28:04.483 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LISA DESJARDINS: Morning in
Baltimore, oven-baked
biscuits and a warm moment for
Victoria Cross

28:04.516 --> 28:07.386 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
and fiance Cameron Okeke (ph).

28:07.419 --> 28:13.225 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Today, Victoria's getting an
IUD, or intrauterine
device, a form of birth control
that works

28:13.258 --> 28:14.960 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
